PN,31809
SC,0009
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F318A1778688714
OL,3,CWhat quirky traditions will be on show
OL,4,Cfor the King's speech?
OL,6,FOver the centuries, and particularly
OL,7,Fduring the turbulent period around the
OL,8,FEnglish Civil Wars in the mid 1600s,
OL,9,Fit came to symbolise the independence
OL,10,Fand privileges of the House of
OL,11,FCommons, and the principle that the
OL,12,Fmonarch governs through Parliament
OL,13,Frather than by personal authority.
OL,15,FThis has given rise to centuries-old
OL,16,Fceremonies which assert the
OL,17,Findependence of the Commons and recall
OL,18,Fan era when Parliament had to defend
OL,19,Fits privileges against direct royal
OL,20,Finterference.
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G9/14
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BNat News CNat TV FClean Feed
FL,319,300,200,140,000,100
PN,31810
SC,0010
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F318A1778688714
OL,3,CWhat quirky traditions will be on show
OL,4,Cfor the King's speech?
OL,6,FBefore the King arrives, the Yeomen of
OL,7,Fthe Guard search the cellars of the
OL,8,FPalace of Westminster for bombs to
OL,9,Fcommemorate the gunpowder plot of 1605.
OL,11,FAnother tradition involves a
OL,12,Fparliamentary official called Black
OL,13,FRod having the door of the Commons
OL,14,Fshut in their face.
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                   G10/14
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BNat News CNat TV FClean Feed
FL,319,300,200,140,000,100
PN,31811
SC,0011
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F318A1778688714
OL,3,CWhat quirky traditions will be on show
OL,4,Cfor the King's speech?
OL,6,FBlack Rod then knocks three times on
OL,7,Fthe door with the rod before they are
OL,8,Ffinally let in. This tradition
OL,9,Fsymbolises the right of the Commons to
OL,10,Fexclude royal messengers, and dates
OL,11,Fback to 1642 when Charles I tried to
OL,12,Farrest five MPs.
OL,14,FFinally, it is also tradition that one
OL,15,FMP is 'held hostage' (conventionally
OL,16,Fthe vice-chamberlain) in Buckingham
OL,17,FPalace while the King is in
OL,18,FParliament, to ensure the monarch's
OL,19,Fsafe return.
OL,21,FWhat will be in the King's speech?
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                   G11/14
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
